## 2. Java Hard Links — High-Level Overview

Since **Java 7 (NIO.2)**, the `java.nio.file` package provides a clean API for
creating hard links through `Files.createLink()`.

### API Signature

```java
public static Path Files.createLink(Path link, Path existing) throws IOException
```

- `link` — the new directory entry to create (the hard link path)
- `existing` — the existing file whose inode the link will point to
- Returns the `link` path on success

### High-Level Usage

```java
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Path;
import java.nio.file.Paths;

// Create a hard link: targetDir/data.txt → sourceDir/data.txt
Path existing = Paths.get("/data/sourceDir/data.txt");
Path link     = Paths.get("/data/targetDir/data.txt");

Files.createLink(link, existing);
```

After this call:
- Both paths point to the **same inode** and the **same data blocks** on disk
- Reading from either path returns identical content
- The file's inode reference count is incremented from 1 to 2
- **No data is copied** — the operation is O(1) in terms of file size

### High-Level Characteristics

| Property              | Value                                          |
|-----------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| Time complexity       | O(1) — independent of file size                |
| Disk space used       | 0 bytes additional (metadata only, ~few bytes) |
| Cross-filesystem      | Not supported — both paths must be on same FS  |
| Atomic                | Yes — creating a link is an atomic FS operation|
| Java version required | Java 7+ (NIO.2)                                |
| Platform support      | Linux, macOS, Windows (NTFS), most POSIX       |

