## 9. Caveats and Constraints

### 9.1 Same-Filesystem Requirement

Hard links can only be created between paths on the **same filesystem/mount point**.
This is enforced at the kernel level — the `link()` system call returns `EXDEV`
("cross-device link") if the paths are on different filesystems.

```java
// This will throw IOException if paths are on different filesystems
try {
    Files.createLink(targetPath, sourcePath);
} catch (IOException e) {
    // Falls back to file copy if hard link fails
    Files.copy(sourcePath, targetPath);
}
```

### 9.2 No Directory Hard Links

Most POSIX filesystems do not allow hard links to directories (to prevent cycles
in the filesystem graph). You must iterate over files and link them individually,
as shown in the `hardLinkDirectory()` method.

### 9.3 Platform-Specific Behavior

| Platform       | Hard Link Support                                    |
|----------------|------------------------------------------------------|
| Linux (ext4)   | Full support                                         |
| Linux (XFS)    | Full support                                         |
| macOS (APFS)   | Full support                                         |
| Windows (NTFS) | Supported via `CreateHardLinkW` (requires privileges)|
| FAT32 / exFAT  | **Not supported** (no inode concept)                 |
| NFS / network  | Depends on server filesystem                         |

### 9.4 Maximum Link Count

Filesystems impose a maximum number of hard links per inode:

| Filesystem | Max Hard Links per Inode |
|------------|--------------------------|
| ext4       | 65,000                   |
| XFS        | ~4 billion               |
| NTFS       | 1,024                    |
| APFS       | No practical limit       |

For index splitting with 10 partitions, this is never a concern.

### 9.5 Backup and Archival Considerations

Some backup tools may not preserve hard link relationships and could create full
copies instead. Verify that your backup solution handles hard links correctly
(e.g., `rsync -H` preserves hard links; `tar` preserves them by default).

