## 10. Summary

### Why Java Hard Links + Lucene Indexes Work So Well

```
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │                                                             │
  │   Lucene's Guarantees          Hard Link's Properties       │
  │   ────────────────────         ──────────────────────       │
  │   • Segment files are         • Multiple paths share       │
  │     WRITE-ONCE / IMMUTABLE      the same data blocks       │
  │                                                             │
  │   • Modifications create      • Writing through one path   │
  │     NEW files                   affects all paths           │
  │                                 (but Lucene never writes    │
  │   • Deletions use separate      to existing segments)       │
  │     .del files                                              │
  │                                                             │
  │   • Merges read old segments  • When old segments are       │
  │     and write new ones          unlinked, reference count   │
  │                                 drops; space is reclaimed   │
  │                                 only when count reaches 0   │
  │                                                             │
  │   ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════   │
  │                                                             │
  │   RESULT: Hard links are 100% safe with Lucene indexes     │
  │           because the shared files are never modified.      │
  │                                                             │
  │   BENEFIT: 1,796x faster than file copy for the link phase │
  │            Zero additional disk space until merge           │
  │            Identical final results                          │
  │                                                             │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

Hard links are not just a performance optimization for Lucene index operations —
they are the **architecturally correct** approach. Lucene's immutable segment
design was built with this kind of filesystem-level sharing in mind, which is why
Lucene itself uses hard links internally (`HardlinkCopyDirectoryWrapper`) for
index replication and directory operations.

For any operation that requires duplicating a Lucene index directory — whether
for splitting, snapshotting, replication, or backup — hard links should be the
**default strategy**, with file copy used only as a fallback when cross-filesystem
operations are required.
